and, United Kingdom","Warburton, Chester, England":"Warburton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Warburton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Warburton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Warburton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Greater Manchester (formerly in Cheshire) called Warburton, from the Old English female personal name <i>Wǣrburg</i> (composed of the elements <i>wǣr</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>burh</i> ‘fortress’) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Warbritton","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Warburton  . This form of the surname is not found in English sources."]},{"name":"Warbington","meanings":["English (Lancashire): perhaps a variant of   Warburton  ; otherwise a habitational name from a lost or unidentified place."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Warburton was born about 1367, in Warburton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John de Warburton II, was 30 and his mother, Agnes de Wevers, was 31. He married Mrs Richard Warburton. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died after 1425."},"et":{"Abt 1367–AFT 1425":"umbes 1367–pärast 1425","1361–1391":"1361–1391","1364–1421":"1364–1421","1367–1425":"1367–1425","1369–Female":"1369–Surnud","1380–1422":"1380–1422","1339–1384":"1339–1384","1337–1420":"1337–1420","AFT 1425":"pärast 1425","1384":"1384","1361":"1361","Abt 1367":"umbes 1367","1380":"1380","Abt 1329":"umbes 1329","1391":"1391","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1369":"1369","1422":"1422","1367":"1367","1421":"1421","1420":"1420","living 1402":"1402","1364":"1364","about 1384":"umbes 1384","after 1422":"pärast 1422","1339":"1339","Warburton, Cheshire, England":"Warburton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warburton, Chester, England":"Warburton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warburton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Warburton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1367–AFT 1425":"noin 1367–1425 jälkeen","1361–1391":"1361–1391","1364–1421":"1364–1421","1367–1425":"1367–1425","1369–Female":"1369–Kuollut","1380–1422":"1380–1422","1339–1384":"1339–1384","1337–1420":"1337–1420","AFT 1425":"1425 jälkeen","1384":"1384","1361":"1361","Abt 1367":"noin 1367","1380":"1380","Abt 1329":"noin 1329","1391":"1391","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1369":"1369","1422":"1422","1367":"1367","